Where is TikTok headed? 🔮

The SEO on TikTok is so powerful that the "seasonality" of content pieces is starting to take shape from past content. 

A seasonal relevant video that was posted a year ago has the potential to start to gain traction & views again later on based on the popularity of that topic at that yearly time. We've seen it happen! 

Plus, it was even found in a study that almost half of Gen Z prefer to do Instagram or TikTok searches instead of Google searches. 🤯

If you want your videos to go viral this season (and next season), it's crucial to use specific keywords that your targeted audience is likely to search for in every video.

Know these 🚩red flags🚩 when working with brands!

If you're new to the Creator/Influencer industry and don't have a lot of experience working with brands yet, it's important to know some big NO-NOs that can hurt your Creator business.

🚩 If a brand asks you to pay for shipping, run away from them! This is typically a scam, you should never pay for shipping if a brand wants to send you a product. 

🚩 If you receive emails from a brand and they're never addressed to you even after you respond a few times, don't waste your time! 

🚩 If a brand refuses to sign a contract, do not work with them. A contract is what will keep you and your work/content safe.

🚩 If they ask for all your content and raw files without paying you for it, say NO! Raw files are VALUABLE and you can tell them that and charge for it.

Answering your content creator questions ➡️ Why do rates vary by niche? 🤔

When a brand wants to work with you, what they really want is access to your audience. Every Creator and every niche is going to have a different situation when it comes to their audience, so that's naturally reflected in the rates they're willing to pay.

It's all about supply and demand.

 As a former Econ Major, let me break it down:

When supply (# of influencers in a specific niche) is greater than demand, rates go down; when demand is greater than supply, rates go up.

So by niching down, you are basically becoming higher in demand because there's less to choose from.

As always, you need to show and tell a brand what your value is when you're pitching to them. Niching down gets a bad rep, but it really does help you build an audience in a way that helps you pitch to brands.
